Limit of Panic
Copenhagen—We often hear that the world as we know it will end, usually through ecological collapse.
In fact, the basic idea has been with us since The Limits to Growth, a harbinger of doom published more than forty years ago by the Club of Rome.
But time is not forgiving.
The Limits to Growth in 1972 warned humanity that a catastrophic collapse was imminent.
But we have seen financial panics instead of any real shortages or production collapses.
Instead, resources created by human ingenuity more than suffice for human consumption.
Yet the basic message of The Limits to Growth still holds: we continue on a trajectory focused on misleading solutions to tangential issues while ignoring major problems and wise solutions.
In the early 1970s, technological optimism waned; the Vietnam War became a disaster; society fell into turmoil; and the economy stagnated.
Rachel Carson’s 1962 book Silent Spring ignited fears of pollution and sparked the modern environmentalist movement; Paul Ehrlich’s 1968 title The Population Bomb summed it up.
On the first Earth Day in 1970, there was widespread pessimism.
The aim of The Limits to Growth was to make people worried about resource depletion.
This is our fate because too many people want to consume too much.
Even if our talents buy us some time, we will ultimately destroy both the Earth and ourselves with pollution.
The only hope is to stagnate economic growth itself, reduce consumption, recycle, and force people to have fewer children, achieving social stability at a significantly poorer level than now.
This idea continues to resonate, despite being fundamentally wrong.
For instance, the authors of The Limits to Growth predicted that the world would run out of aluminum, copper, gold, lead, mercury, molybdenum, natural gas, oil, silver, tin, tungsten, and zinc before 2013.
Yet, even with recent rebounds in commodity prices, they have overall fallen to about one-third of their levels a century and a half ago.
Technological innovation has replaced mercury in batteries, dental materials, and thermometers; by 2000, mercury consumption had dropped by 98%, and prices had fallen by 90%.
More broadly, since 1946, supplies of copper, aluminum, iron, and zinc have exceeded demand, thanks to discoveries of new reserves and more efficient refining techniques.
Similarly, oil and natural gas were expected to be depleted by 1990 and 1992, respectively; today, both have reserves above 1970 levels despite a significant increase in consumption.
In the past six years, shale gas alone has doubled America's potential natural gas resources and halved prices.
As for economic collapse, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change estimates that global per capita GDP will increase fourteenfold this century, with developing countries increasing twenty-fourfold.
The Limits to Growth was wrong because the authors overlooked the greatest resource of all: our own ingenuity.
Population growth began slowing in the 1960s.
Food supply did not collapse (15 billion hectares of arable land are being used, with an additional 27 billion hectares in reserve).
Malnutrition rates have been halved, dropping from 35% of the world's population to 16%.
Pollution has also not proven problematic for us.
The Club of Rome imagined a pastoral past where we had no particulate air pollution and were all happy farmers, while in the future, smokestacks would make us unable to breathe. Reality is quite the opposite.
In 1900, the global population was only 1.5 billion, and nearly three million people – equivalent to one person out of every 500 – died each year from air pollution, most of which was indoor air pollution.
Today, that number has dropped to one death per 2000 people.
While pollution-related deaths still exceed those from malaria, the mortality rate is falling, not rising.
Nevertheless, the ideas fostered by The Limits to Growth continue to shape the thinking of both the public and the elite.
Take recycling, for example, which is often little more than a feel-good gesture that is costly to the environment and ineffective.
For instance, paper usually comes from sustainable forests rather than tropical rainforests.
Programs and government subsidies related to paper recycling result in low-quality paper, protecting resources that are not under threat.
Similarly, policies worrying about overpopulation leading to self-destruction, such as China’s one-child policy and India’s forced sterilization.
In addition, although pesticides and other pollutants were believed to kill half of humanity, good pesticide regulation resulted in only 20 annual deaths in the United States, while the use of pesticides created cheaper and more abundant food supplies.
Indeed, relying solely on organic agriculture – the movement spurred by pesticide panic – would cost the US an additional $100 billion annually.
Agricultural efficiency would decrease by 16%, requiring an additional 65 million hectares of farmland – half the size of modern-day California – to maintain current output.
Rising prices will lead to a decrease in fruit and vegetable consumption, resulting in severe negative health impacts (including thousands more cancer deaths annually).
Fixating on dark scenarios prevents us from addressing the real global threats.
Poverty is one of the biggest killers, with easily treatable diseases still causing the death of 15 million people annually – equivalent to a quarter of all deaths.
The solution lies in economic growth.
Once people escape poverty, most can afford the burden of preventing infectious diseases.
In the past three decades, 680 million people in China have escaped poverty, leading the world in reducing nearly one billion poor people.
This has resulted in widespread improvements in health, life expectancy, and quality of life.
The four-decade history since The Limits to Growth was published shows that we need more growth, not less.
The expansion of trade is estimated to bring over $100 trillion in benefits annually by the end of this century, far surpassing the meager gains from fear-mongering policies that create a sense of security through inaction.
But this requires abandoning anti-growth thinking and using our infinite potential to create a brighter future.
